In early July 2017, Musk forecast at least six months of serious production difficulties.<ref name="wired.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/musk-model-3-tesla-production-delays-january/|title=Tesla Delays Its Model 3 Production Goals – Again|website=Wired.com|access-date=January 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104005556/https://www.wired.com/story/musk-model-3-tesla-production-delays-january/|archive-date=January 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla's announced goal at that time was to produce 1,500 units in the third quarter of 2017, increasing to 5,000 per week by end of December 2017,<ref name="bloomberg.com">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-02/tesla-sales-climb-as-model-3-stokes-demand-in-pricier-offerings |title=Tesla Falters With Model 3 as Initial Output Trails Forecast |date=October 2, 2017 |access-date=October 5, 2017 |via=Bloomberg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005033035/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-02/tesla-sales-climb-as-model-3-stokes-demand-in-pricier-offerings |archive-date=October 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> but only 260 vehicles were manufactured during the third quarter. The company blamed production bottlenecks, but said there were "no fundamental issues with the Model 3 production or supply chain" and expressed confidence about its ability to resolve the bottlenecks in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/10/02/we-understand-what-needs-to-be-fixed-tesla-says-after-bungling-model-3-production-goals/|title=‘We understand what needs to be fixed,' Tesla says after missing Model 3 production goals|first=Peter|last=Holley|date=October 2, 2017|publisher=|access-date=October 5, 2017|via=Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005002440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/10/02/we-understand-what-needs-to-be-fixed-tesla-says-after-bungling-model-3-production-goals/|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-teslas-production-delays-parts-of-model-3-were-being-made-by-hand-1507321057 |title=Behind Tesla's Production Delays: Parts of Model 3 Were Being Made by Hand |first=Tim |last=Higgins |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |date=October 6, 2017 |access-date=October 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008002200/https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-teslas-production-delays-parts-of-model-3-were-being-made-by-hand-1507321057 |archive-date=October 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Tesla delivered just 1,542 Model 3 cars in the fourth quarter of 2017,<ref name=Tesla4Q2017final>{{cite press release |url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/4934165653x0x970775/34923C55-6853-4223-ADDA-CB3CDC1B919F/TSLA_Update_Letter_2017-4Q.pdf |title=Tesla Fourth Quarter & Full Year 2017 Update |publisher=Tesla |work=Tesla |location=[[Palo Alto]] |date=February 7, 2017 |accessdate=February 7, 2018 |quote=In Q4, we delivered 28,425 Model S and Model X vehicles and 1,542 Model 3 vehicles, totaling 29,967 deliveries. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208182745/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/4934165653x0x970775/34923C55-6853-4223-ADDA-CB3CDC1B919F/TSLA_Update_Letter_2017-4Q.pdf |archive-date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> about 2,900 less than Wall Street estimations, which were already halved previously after Tesla published the company's third quarter report.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/transportation/autos/another-missed-promise-teslas-latest-model-3-production-setback-could-mean-company-needs-more-cash|title=‘Another missed promise': Tesla's latest Model 3 production setback could mean company needs more cash|date=January 4, 2018|website=FinancialPost.com|access-date=January 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106002158/http://business.financialpost.com/transportation/autos/another-missed-promise-teslas-latest-model-3-production-setback-could-mean-company-needs-more-cash|archive-date=January 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By early November 2017, Musk had postponed the target date for manufacturing 5,000 of the vehicles per week from December 2017 to March 2018.<ref name="auto">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/11/03/sleepless-nights-broken-robots-and-mounting-pressure-musk-offers-rare-glimpse-inside-teslas-production-hell/ |title=Analysis – Sleepless nights, broken robots and mounting pressure: Musk offers rare glimpse inside Tesla's ‘production hell' |first=Peter |last=Holley |date=November 3, 2017 |access-date=November 5, 2017 |work=Washington Post |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171105050608/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2017/11/03/sleepless-nights-broken-robots-and-mounting-pressure-musk-offers-rare-glimpse-inside-teslas-production-hell/ |archive-date=November 5, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="fortune.com"/><ref name="auto"/> An analyst with Cowan and Company, an investment banking firm, said in November 2017 that "Elon Musk needs to stop over-promising and under-delivering".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-reaction/tesla-must-stop-overpromising-could-need-more-finance-analysts-idUSKBN1D21A3 |title=Tesla must stop overpromising, could need more finance: analysts |work=Reuters |date=November 2, 2017 |access-date=November 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104234749/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results-reaction/tesla-must-stop-overpromising-could-need-more-finance-analysts-idUSKBN1D21A3 |archive-date=November 4, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prior to a planned shutdown in mid-April 2018 to further increase production, Tesla produced more than 2,000 Model 3 vehicles for three straight weeks.<ref name=Tesla1Q2018final/> Customer deliveries totaled 1,764 units in 2017.<ref name=Tesla3Q2017final>{{cite web|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/5846881552x0x962149/00F6EB90-2695-44E6-8C03-7EC4E06DF840/TSLA|title=_Update_Letter_2017-3Q.pdf Tesla Third Quarter 2017 Update|publisher=Tesla|date=November 1, 2017|accessdate=May 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111165022/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/5846881552x0x962149/00F6EB90-2695-44E6-8C03-7EC4E06DF840/TSLA|archive-date=January 11, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Tesla4Q2017final/>

Deliveries totaled 8,182 units in the first quarter of 2018, 18,449 in the second, and rose to 55,840 units in the third.<ref name=Tesla1Q2018final/><ref name="Tesla2Q2018final"/><ref name="Tesla3Q2018"/> Global deliveries passed the 100,000 unit milestone in October 2018.<ref name=100kModel3>{{cite web |url=https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1119793_finalist-for-green-car-reports-best-car-to-buy-2019-tesla-model-3 |title=Finalist for Green Car Reports Best Car To Buy 2019: Tesla Model 3 |work=Green Car Reports |first=Bengt |last=Halvorson |date=November 8, 2018 |accessdate=November 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110040640/https://www.greencarreports.com/news/1119793_finalist-for-green-car-reports-best-car-to-buy-2019-tesla-model-3 |archive-date=November 10, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sales in the fourth quarter achieved a record of 63,359 units, totaling 146,055 units delivered during the first full year of production,<ref name=Tesla1Q2018final>{{cite web|url=http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x979026/44C49236-1FC2-4FD9-80B1-495ED74E4194/TSLA_Update_Letter_2018-1Q.pdf|title=Tesla First Quarter 2018 Update|publisher=Tesla|accessdate=May 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527202413/http://files.shareholder.com/downloads/ABEA-4CW8X0/3853068125x0x979026/44C49236-1FC2-4FD9-80B1-495ED74E4194/TSLA_Update_Letter_2018-1Q.pdf|archive-date=May 27, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Tesla2Q2018final"/><ref name="Tesla3Q2018"/><ref name=Tesla4Q2018final/> making the Model 3 the world's best selling plug-in electric car in 2018.<ref name=Top20Global2018>{{cite web| url=http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2019/01/global-top-20-december-2018.html| title=Global Top 20 - December 2018| last=Jose| first=Pontes| publisher=EVSales.com| date=January 31, 2019| accessdate=February 2, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013624/http://ev-sales.blogspot.com/2019/01/global-top-20-december-2018.html| archive-date=February 1, 2019| url-status=live}} "Global sales totaled 2,018,247 plug-in passenger cars in 2018, with a BEV:PHEV ratio of 69:31, and a market share of 2.1%. The world's top selling plug-in car was the Tesla Model 3, and Tesla was the top selling manufacturer of plug-in passenger cars in 2018, followed by BYD."</ref> Retail deliveries in Europe and China began in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/more-tesla-model-3-norway/ |title=More And More Tesla Model 3 Reach Norway: Sales Imminent |last=Kane |first=Mark |work=InsideEVs |date=February 16, 2019 |access-date=February 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216212131/https://insideevs.com/more-tesla-model-3-norway/ |archive-date=February 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-arrive-china-port-deliveries/ |title=Tesla Model 3s Arrive In Chinese Port Ready For Deliveries |work=Gasgoo News |publisher=InsideEVs |date=February 13, 2019 |access-date=February 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217142219/https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-arrive-china-port-deliveries/ |archive-date=February 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cumulative sales since inception totaled 371,022 units up to September 2019.<ref name=Tesla3Q2017final/><ref name=Tesla4Q2017final/><ref name=Tesla4Q2018final/><ref name=Tesla1Q2019>{{cite pressrelease |publisher=Tesla |url=http://ir.tesla.com/news-releases/news-release-details/tesla-q1-2019-vehicle-production-deliveries |title=Tesla Q1 2019 Vehicle Production & Deliveries |location=Palo Alto |date=April 3, 2019 |accessdate=April 13, 2019 |quote=About 50,900 Model 3 vehicles were delivered in the first quarter of 2019. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412233803/https://ir.tesla.com/news-releases/news-release-details/tesla-q1-2019-vehicle-production-deliveries |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Delivery of the first right-hand drive vehicles began in June 2019, starting with the UK<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla Model 3: first UK buyers take delivery of cars |url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/tesla-model-3-first-uk-buyers-take-delivery-cars |accessdate=July 5, 2019 |publisher=AUTOCAR |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190705142213/https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/tesla-model-3-first-uk-buyers-take-delivery-cars |archive-date=July 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and later in Australia and New Zealand. In Australia in September 2019, it is estimated that Tesla sold 1500 cars that equates to around 5 per cent of the monthly sales of all new passenger vehicles in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reneweconomy.com.au/tesla-model-3-electric-vehicle-smashes-sales-records-recasts-australia-car-market-14414/|title=Tesla Model 3 electric vehicle smashes sales records, recasts Australia car market|last=Parkinson|first=Giles|date=2019-10-02|website=RenewEconomy|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-01-19}}</ref>

[[File:Tesla Model 3 DCA 08 2018 0159.jpg|thumb|left|The Tesla Model 3 listed in 2018 as the best selling plug-in car in California, the U.S. and the world.<ref name=Top20Global2018/><ref name="US2018Tesla"/><ref name=Cal2018/>]]

During the first half of 2018, the Model 3 was the top-selling [[alternative fuel vehicle]] in California with 12,674 units, followed by the [[Toyota Prius]] conventional [[hybrid electric vehicle|hybrid]] (10,043).<ref name=AFV2Q2018CA>{{cite web |url=https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Alt-Powertrain-Report-3Q-18-Release.pdf |title=California Green Vehicle Report (YTD June 2018) |author=California New Car Dealers Association (CNCDA) |publisher=CNCDA |date=August 2018 |accessdate=October 24, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025071221/https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Alt-Powertrain-Report-3Q-18-Release.pdf |archive-date=October 25, 2018 |url-status=live }} ''See section: "Electric and Plug In Vehicle Segments Move Higher in 2018" - registrations through December March 2018 since 2014.''</ref> The Model 3 became the best-selling car by revenue in North America for the months July and August 2018, with monthly sales of {{USD|993 million}} for August 2018, beating the [[Toyota Camry]] at {{USD|765 million}}, and [[Honda Accord]] at {{USD| 679 million}}.<ref name="grinshpun-2018-09-09">{{cite news|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2018/09/09/tesla-model-3-becomes-1-best-selling-car-in-the-us/|work=Clean Technica|title=Tesla Model 3 = #1 Best Selling Car In The US (In Revenue)|first=Michael|last=Grinshpun|date=September 9, 2018|accessdate=September 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909220239/https://cleantechnica.com/2018/09/09/tesla-model-3-becomes-1-best-selling-car-in-the-us/|archive-date=September 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> By October 2018, Bloomberg reported that, in the U.S. market, Tesla Model 3 sales made it the fifth best-selling sedan in the previous quarter, behind the Toyota Camry and Corolla and the Honda Civic and Accord models, but ahead of Nissan Sentra and Altima, Hyundai Elantra, Ford Fusion, and Chevrolet Cruze and Malibu models.<ref name=bloomberg20181005>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-03/tesla-s-model-3-is-becoming-one-of-america-s-best-selling-sedans |title=Tesla’s Model 3 Is Becoming One of America’s Best-Selling Sedans |work=Bloomberg L.P. |date=October 3, 2018 |access-date=October 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004115313/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-10-03/tesla-s-model-3-is-becoming-one-of-america-s-best-selling-sedans |archive-date=October 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>

U.S. sales of the Model 3 reached the 100,000 unit milestone in November 2018, hitting this milestone quicker than any previous model sold in the country.<ref name=Model3US100K>{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-sales-november-u-s-2018/ |title=Tesla Model 3 Sales Charge Way Past Milestone Of 100,000 In U.S. |first=Eric |last=Loveday |publisher=InsideEVs.com |date=December 4, 2018 |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205023220/https://insideevs.com/tesla-model-3-sales-november-u-s-2018/ |archive-date=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Model 3 was the top-selling [[plug-in electric car]] in the U.S. for 12 months in a row since January 2018, ending 2018 as the best-selling plug-in with an estimated all-time record of 139,782 units delivered, the first time a plug-in car sold more than 100,000 units in one year.<ref name="US2018Tesla">{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/u-s-tesla-sales-december-2018-up/ |title=U.S. Tesla Sales In December 2018 Up By 249% |author=Mark Kane |work=Inside EVs |date=January 3, 2019 |access-date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109111016/https://insideevs.com/u-s-tesla-sales-december-2018-up/ |archive-date=January 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="US2018sales">{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/december-2018-u-s-ev-sales-recap/ |title=December 2018 U.S. EV Sales Recap: Over 360K Secured! |author=Steven Loveday |work=Inside EVs |date=January 7, 2019 |access-date=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109155412/https://insideevs.com/december-2018-u-s-ev-sales-recap/ |archive-date=January 9, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=TopUS2018>{{cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-december-2018/ | title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: December 2018 | first=Mark | last=Kane | publisher=InsideEVs.com | date=January 24, 2019 | accessdate=January 24, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125020449/https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-december-2018/ | archive-date=January 25, 2019 | url-status=live }} ''See Graph: "Top 10 U.S. Plug-in cars (cumulative sales)" and "U.S. Plug-in Car Sales (cumulative)"''</ref> Additionally, the Model 3 ranked as the best-selling [[luxury vehicle]] in the American market in 2018.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/niallmccarthy/2019/02/08/the-tesla-model-3-was-the-best-selling-luxury-car-in-america-last-year-infographic/#4589e2407b07 | title=The Tesla Model 3 Was The Best-Selling Luxury Car In America Last Year [Infographic] | first=Niall | last=McCarthy | work=[[Forbes]] | date=February 8, 2019 | accessdate=February 23, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223184549/https://www.forbes.com/sites/niallmccarthy/2019/02/08/the-tesla-model-3-was-the-best-selling-luxury-car-in-america-last-year-infographic/#4589e2407b07 | archive-date=February 23, 2019 | url-status=live }} See infographic.</ref>

The Model 3 also topped plug-in electric car sales in California in 2018, with 51,293 units registered, as well as the state's best selling car in the [[Near-luxury car|near luxury category]].<ref name=Cal2018>{{cite web |url=https://insideevs.com/california-electric-car-sales-2018/ |title=Electric Cars Outsell Hybrids In California: Tesla Model 3 Tops In Class |first=Mark |last=Kane |work=Inside EVs |date=February 21, 2019 |access-date=February 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222225542/https://insideevs.com/california-electric-car-sales-2018/ |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Calif4Q2018>{{cite web |url=https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-18.pdf |title=New Vehicle Registrations Remained Above 2 million Units in 2018 |author=California New Car Dealers Association (CNCDA) |publisher=CNCDA |date=February 2019 |accessdate=February 21, 2019 |volume=15 |number=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222152029/https://www.cncda.org/wp-content/uploads/Cal-Covering-4Q-18.pdf |archive-date=February 22, 2019 |url-status=live }} ''See section: "Electric Vehicle Registrations Increased Sharply in 2018" - Figures for 2017 were revised.''</ref> In January 2019, the car overtook the Model S to become the U.S. all-time best selling all-electric car,<ref name=Top3US012019>{{cite web | url=https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-january-2019/ | title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: January 2019 | first=Mark | last=Kane | publisher=InsideEVs.com | date=February 4, 2019 | accessdate=February 6, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020207/https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-january-2019/ | archive-date=February 7, 2019 | url-status=live }} ''See Graph: "Top 10 U.S. Plug-in cars (cumulative sales)" In January 209 the Tesla Model 3 (148,046) overtook the Model S (144,767). The Chevrolet Volt (152,819) continues as the all-time best selling plug-in car in the U.S.''</ref> and, the next month, also passed the [[Chevrolet Volt]] to become the all-time top selling plug-in electric car in the U.S.<ref name=Top3US022019/> Since inception, an estimated 163,979 Model 3 cars have been delivered in the American market up to March 2019.<ref name=Top3US2019>{{cite web |url=https://thedriven.io/2019/04/15/tesla-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-selling-electric-car-in-us/ |title=Tesla Model 3 becomes all-time best-selling electric car in US |author=Bridie Schmidt |work=EV Adoption |publisher=The Driven |date=April 15, 2019 |accessdate=April 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415120510/https://thedriven.io/2019/04/15/tesla-model-3-becomes-all-time-best-selling-electric-car-in-us/ |archive-date=April 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-march-2019/| title=US Plug-In Electric Car Sales Charted: March 2019| first=Mark| last=Kane| publisher=InsideEVs.com| date=April 7, 2019| accessdate=April 13, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413145955/https://insideevs.com/us-plug-in-electric-car-sales-charted-march-2019/| archive-date=April 13, 2019| url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2018, Elon Musk predicted that eventual global demand would likely be between 500,000 and {{nowrap|1 million}} Model 3 cars per year— ranking in between the [[BMW 3 Series]] and the [[Volkswagen Golf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LTjggW0uXBw&t=33m |first=Elon|last=Musk|author-link=Elon Musk |date=October 25, 2018|title=Tesla 2018 Q3 Earnings Call|via=Youtube|format=offset 33:00|quote=likely global demand for Model 3... it's probably on the order of anyway from 500,000 to a million cars a year, let's say, … as quick global demand for Model 3.  If you look at something like BWM 3 Series … [[BMW 3 Series]] is about half-a-million a year, globally.  And generally we find that we outcompete the BMW 3 Series quite well, so it seems logical therefore that we would have higher production …higher demand, you know;  maybe somewhere between the BMW 3 Series and the [[Volkswagen Golf]] which is about a million units a year.}}</ref>

Similar to how the first US-made Model 3s were delivered to employees in July 2017, the first Chinese-made Model 3 cars were delivered to employees at the end of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tesla delivers first China-made Model 3s to its own workers |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/30/tech/tesla-china-model-3/index.html |website=CNN |date=December 30, 2019 |access-date=December 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230144848/https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/30/tech/tesla-china-model-3/index.html |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

