===Concerns===
In May 2018, [[Consumer Reports]] found "big flaws, such as long stopping distances in our emergency braking test and difficult-to-use controls", finding the braking distance was worse than a Ford F-150 full-size truck, and branding the Model 3 "not recommended".  Tesla responded to the claims with concern and, over the next weekend, released an [[Over-the-air programming|OTA update]] for the anti-lock braking algorithm.  Consumer Reports, impressed with the prompt OTA update, verified the improved braking performance and changed their rating to a recommended model.<ref name="Consumer Reports May 30, 2018 braking update">{{cite web |title=Tesla Model 3 Gets CR Recommendation After Braking Update |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/car-safety/tesla-model-3-gets-cr-recommendation-after-braking-update/ |first=Patrick |last=Olsen |work=Consumer Reports |location=US |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=June 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531211817/https://www.consumerreports.org/car-safety/tesla-model-3-gets-cr-recommendation-after-braking-update/ |archive-date=May 31, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Wired May 30, 2018 brake fix OTA">{{cite web |last1=Marshall |first1=Aarian |title=Tesla’s Quick Fix for Its Braking System Came From the Ether |url=https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model3-braking-software-update-consumer-reports/ |work=Wired |location=US |date=May 30, 2018 |access-date=June 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019115808/https://www.wired.com/story/tesla-model3-braking-software-update-consumer-reports/ |archive-date=October 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2019, Consumer Reports revoked the Model 3 recommendation because "many customers have reported problems with the [car], including loose body trim and glass defects."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/21/tech/consumer-reports-tesla-model-3/index.html|title=Consumer Reports no longer recommends the Tesla Model 3|work=[[CNN Business]]|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=February 21, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190221194657/https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/21/tech/consumer-reports-tesla-model-3/index.html|archive-date=February 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> As with Model S and Model X, Model 3 production flaws were reduced over time.<ref name=bloombergSurvey>{{cite web |author1=Tom Randall, Dean Halford and Cedric Sam |title=The Tesla Model 3 Survey 5,000 Tesla Owners Told Us What Elon Musk Got Right and Wrong |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2019-tesla-model-3-survey/ |website=www.bloomberg.com |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=October 29, 2019 |access-date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029164702/https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2019-tesla-model-3-survey/ |archive-date=October 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  In November 2019, Consumer Reports reinstated the Model 3 recommendation, claiming it was the fifth-most reliable of twelve compact luxury cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/11/15/tesla-model-3-s-consumer-reports-recommended-list/|title=Tesla's Model 3 and S are (once again) recommended by 'Consumer Reports'|work=[[Engadget]]|last=Moon|first=Mariella|date=November 15, 2019|accessdate=November 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117060147/https://www.engadget.com/2019/11/15/tesla-model-3-s-consumer-reports-recommended-list/|archive-date=November 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

During long-term testing of a Model 3 in December 2019, ''Car and Driver'' experienced a rear [[inverter]] [[short circuit|short]] after 5,286 miles and 3 months of ownership.<ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30383959/tesla-model-3-repaired-after-breakdown/</ref>  It was their first long-term vehicle to suffer such a major failure while parked.<ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a30361800/tesla-model-3-long-term-failure-stranded-while-parked/</ref>

In 2020, due to the coronavirus outbreak, closure of the Shanghai factory at the end of January, and supply chain issues, Tesla used the 2.5 version processor instead of the 3.0 processor that Chinese users expected to find in their vehicles. This led to mass complaints. Tesla promised to upgrade the hardware free of charge once the supply chain is restored.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-51736405|title=Tesla downgraded Chinese car tech because of virus|date=2020-03-04|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-05|language=en-GB}}</ref> 

== Specifications ==
[[File:First Model 3 production cars ready for delivery.jpg|thumb|First production Tesla Model 3 cars ready for the delivery event on July 28, 2017]]

=== Engineering and changes ===
As production began in 2017, the base Model 3 was announced to have a 50-kWh battery with a range of about {{convert|220|miles|abbr=out}} while the optional 75-kWh battery would have a range of about {{convert|310|miles|abbr=out}}.<ref name=Battery/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://futurism.com/take-an-in-depth-look-at-the-tesla-model-3s-new-battery-pack-architecture/ |title=Take an In-Depth Look at the Tesla Model 3's New Battery Pack Architecture|date=August 25, 2017|access-date=November 6, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107015125/https://futurism.com/take-an-in-depth-look-at-the-tesla-model-3s-new-battery-pack-architecture/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla did not produce base Model 3s in 2017 or 2018. The battery uses [[2170 battery|2170]]-size lithium-ion cells<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/24/tesla-model-3-exclusive-battery-pack-architecture/ |title=Tesla Model 3: Exclusive first look at Tesla's new battery pack architecture|date=August 24, 2017|access-date=November 6, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003616/https://electrek.co/2017/08/24/tesla-model-3-exclusive-battery-pack-architecture/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Tesla Model 3 battery options">{{cite news |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-partner-panasonic-20-30-percent-energy-density-increase// |title=Tesla partner Panasonic says 30% energy density increase in lithium-ion batteries possible |first=Carolyn |last=F |website=Teslarati |date=April 10, 2017 |access-date=November 6, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022854/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-partner-panasonic-20-30-percent-energy-density-increase// |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

As of 2017, the 350-volt Model 3 battery pack was made of four longitudinal modules each containing the individual battery cells.<ref name="electrek-20170824"/> The Standard Range version carries 2,976 cells arranged in groups of 31.<ref name="electrek-20170824"/> The Long Range version carries 4,416 cells arranged in groups of 46,<ref name="electrek-20170824">{{cite news |url=https://electrek.co/2017/08/24/tesla-model-3-exclusive-battery-pack-architecture/ |title=Tesla Model 3: Exclusive first look at Tesla's new battery pack architecture |first=Fred |last=Lambert |work=Electrek |date=August 24, 2017 |access-date=August 24, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170827043849/https://electrek.co/2017/08/24/tesla-model-3-exclusive-battery-pack-architecture/ |archive-date=August 27, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{update after|2019|1|25|reason=Need a more recent source to verify what the updated Model 3 pack consists of in 2019, with several incremental improvements in 2170 battery cell technology that Musk has mentioned}} and weighs<ref name=epa2017>{{cite web |last1=Govindasamy |first1=Kannan |title=RequestforissuanceofanewcertificateofConformity– Initial application for MY2017 Model 3 ‐ Touring |url=https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp?docid=40001&flag=1 |publisher=Environmental Protection Agency |date=June 21, 2017 |access-date=May 25, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190525092128/https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp%3Fdocid%3D40001%26flag%3D1 |archive-date=May 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{Convert|480|kg|lbs|order=flip|abbr=}} in a 0.40 m³ volume; a density of 150 Wh/kg.<ref name=tm3conf2019>{{cite web |title=Request for issuance of a new certificate of Conformity |url=https://iaspub.epa.gov/otaqpub/display_file.jsp?docid=46584&flag=1 |page=36 |date=January 28, 2019}}<!--includes [[Monroney sticker]]s to upload, like https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Electric_99mpge_500px.jpg --></ref><ref name=cleantechnica2018-07-09>{{cite web |last1=Arcus |first1=Christopher |title=Tesla Model 3 & Chevy Bolt Battery Packs Examined |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2018/07/08/tesla-model-3-chevy-bolt-battery-packs-examined/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=July 9, 2018 |access-date=December 1, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191210192933/https://cleantechnica.com/2018/07/08/tesla-model-3-chevy-bolt-battery-packs-examined/ |archive-date=December 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Tesla continues to improve the design of the 2170 battery cell and introduces incremental improvements into the manufacturing line periodically.<ref name=cleantechnica20190105>{{cite web|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/01/05/tesla-gigafactory-tour-shows-why-teslas-batteries-constantly-improving/ |title=Tesla Gigafactory Tour Shows Where Tesla Continuously Drives Down Battery Costs|date=January 6, 2019|website=CleanTechnica|access-date=January 25, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190126000724/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/01/05/tesla-gigafactory-tour-shows-why-teslas-batteries-constantly-improving/ |archive-date=January 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Tesla began manufacture of the "lighter, better, cheaper"<ref name=electrek20181113/> 2170 cell during 2018, with a company goal of reducing the [[cost]] of assembled battery packs to {{USD|100 per kilowatt-hour (kWh)}} by December 2018, and moving the new cell into volume production at Giga Nevada during the first quarter of 2019. [[Electrek]] reported in late 2018 that the improved battery cell design was needed to further reduce battery costs as Tesla was planning to begin to deliver the Model 3 Standard Range for the promised base price of {{USD|35,000}} the following year.<ref name=electrek20181113>[https://electrek.co/2018/11/13/tesla-battery-cells-improved/ Tesla is working on new and improved battery cells] {{Webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190126164251/https://electrek.co/2018/11/13/tesla-battery-cells-improved/ |date=January 26, 2019 }}, Electrek, November 13, 2018, accessed January 26, 2019.</ref>{{update after|2019|10|1|df=US}}<!-- did they achieve this goal of 100 per kilowatt-hour by the date they intended? -->

The inverter for the Model 3 drive unit uses 24 pairs of [[Silicon Carbide#Power electronic devices|Silicon Carbide]] (SiC) [[MOSFET]] chips rated for 650 volts{{clarify|is it known what the model is? can we ascertain what the current specification is? so as to improve the encyclopedic description here.|date=January 2020}} each.<ref>{{cite report|url=http://www.systemplus.fr/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/SP18413-STM_SiC_Module_Tesla_Model_3_Inverter_sample-3.pdf |title=STMicroelectronics SiC Module in Tesla Model3 Inverter|publisher=SystemPlus Consulting|date=June 25, 2018|first=Elena|last=Barbarini|quote=full SiC power module, in its Model 3. … STMicroelectronics … Tesla inverter … 24 1-in-1 power modules … module contains two [[Silicon Carbide|SiC]] MOSFETs}}</ref>

In July 2018, media reported that a Model 3 prototype was seen in California and Nevada while towing a trailer in an apparent evaluation of a [[tow bar]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://electrek.co/2018/07/31/tesla-model-3-towing-capacity/ |title= Tesla Model 3 spotted testing towing capacity |work= Electrek |first= Fred |last= Lambert |date= July 31, 2018 |access-date= April 13, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190530225729/https://electrek.co/2018/07/31/tesla-model-3-towing-capacity/ |archive-date= May 30, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> In May 2019 Tesla started offering an optional tow bar rated for {{convert|2000|lb|kg}} available with Standard Range Plus and Long Range for the European Model 3.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/model3/design?redirect=no#paint |title= Design your Model 3 |website= tesla.com |access-date= May 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://electrek.co/2019/05/08/tesla-model-3-tow-hitch/ |title= Tesla launches tow hitch for Model 3 |work= Electrek |first= Fred |last= Lambert |date= May 8, 2019 |access-date= June 28, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190605191349/https://electrek.co/2019/05/08/tesla-model-3-tow-hitch/ |archive-date= June 5, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/videos/model-3-tow-hitch |title= Model 3 Tow Hitch|website= tesla.com|access-date= May 14, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190519194744/https://www.tesla.com/en_GB/videos/model-3-tow-hitch |archive-date= May 19, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref> Towing a trailer may increase consumption by 40%.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klender |first1=Joey |title=Tesla Model 3 takes on World War II-era trailer in range efficiency towing test |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-towing-range-impact/ |website=TESLARATI |date=13 March 2020 |quote=448 Watt-hours per mile (Wh/mile) .. with trailer. 320 Wh/mi .. without a trailer. |url-status=live}}</ref>

The Model 3 uses regenerative braking, which was tweaked and improved in October 2018 via a software update.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2018/10/25/tesla-model-3-regenerative-braking-software-update/ |title=Tesla improves regenerative braking on Model 3 through over-the-air software update|first=Fred|last=Lambert |date=October 25, 2018|publisher=|access-date=October 25, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181026064538/https://electrek.co/2018/10/25/tesla-model-3-regenerative-braking-software-update/ |archive-date=October 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>

In October 2019, Tesla released a software update including a 5% power upgrade and peak power optimization to owners of the Model 3, via software version 2019.36.2.1, which showed noticeable improvements in acceleration and overall speed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-acceleration-boost-upgrade-2k/ |title=Tesla is hinting at a paid ‘Acceleration Boost’ upgrade for the Model 3 |website=teslarati.com |access-date=December 21, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191222011924/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-model-3-acceleration-boost-upgrade-2k/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2019, Tesla offered Long Range dual-motor Model 3 owners who had software version 2019.40.2 the option to purchase a US$2000 "Acceleration Boost" software upgrade enabling a Sport driving mode,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2019/12/19/tesla-model-3-speed-boost/ |title=Tesla Model 3 owners can go quicker with a click| website=autoblog.com |access-date= December 21, 2019}}</ref> advertised to reduce 0-60 mph time from 4.4s to 3.9s.  Road testing confirmed better-than-expected acceleration with drivers in Sport mode reaching 0-60&nbsp;mph in 3.67s from standstill and 3.47s with a 1&nbsp;foot rollout.<ref name="teslamotorsclub.com Dragy 0-60mph Results">{{cite web |url=https://teslamotorsclub.com/tmc/attachments/3-67zeroto60-png.489974/ |title=teslamotorsclub.com Dragy 0-60mph Results |website=teslamotorsclub.com |access-date=December 21, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191222004547/https://teslamotorsclub.com/tmc/attachments/3-67zeroto60-png.489974/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

The Model 3 is mostly steel, with some aluminum.<ref name=nikkei2016-09-12>{{cite news |url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Tech-Science/Tech/The-company-that-helps-Tesla-make-aluminum-look-sexy?page=2 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160913201501/http://asia.nikkei.com/Tech-Science/Tech/The-company-that-helps-Tesla-make-aluminum-look-sexy?page=2 |title=The company that helps Tesla make aluminum look sexy |first=Yoshifumi |last=Uesaka |date=September 12, 2016 |archivedate=September 13, 2016 |url-status=live |newspaper=[[Nikkei Asian Review]]|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> The {{cvt|185| cm|ft}} width was chosen to fit with [[automated parking system]]s in Japan. Due to its smaller size, the Model 3 is expected to consume less energy than the future Model Y, and thus have longer range.<ref name="ct2019-06-08">{{cite web |last1=Field |first1=Kyle |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190821223314/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/08/streamlining-manufacturing-of-the-tesla-model-3-for-the-model-y/ |archivedate=2019-08-21 |url-status=live |title=Streamlining Manufacturing Of The Tesla Model 3 For The Model Y |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/06/08/streamlining-manufacturing-of-the-tesla-model-3-for-the-model-y/ |website=CleanTechnica |date=June 8, 2019 |quote=the Model Y is notably larger than the Model 3 and has a larger frontal surface area as a result. Combined with its 8–10% heavier build, that will result in a lower efficiency than the 3}}</ref>

Traditional [[Electronic stability control|stability control]] is not made for dual-motor control or the faster response time in electric motors, and Tesla modified the control unit.<ref name=tu2019-05-24>{{cite web |last1=Valle |first1=Marius |title=How Tesla engineers work with Model 3 |url=https://translate.google.com/translate?sl=no&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.tu.no%2Fartikler%2Fslik-jobber-teslas-ingeniorer-med-model-3%2F465394 |publisher=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]] |date=May 24, 2019 |quote=https://www.tu.no/artikler/slik-jobber-teslas-ingeniorer-med-model-3/465394}}</ref> The motors have magnets arranged in a [[Halbach array]].<ref name="ct2019-04-29">{{cite web |title=Industry Expert On Tesla's Motors: "They've Got Magic!" |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/28/industry-expert-on-teslas-motors-theyve-got-magic/ |website=CleanTechnica |date= April 29, 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190921053750/https://cleantechnica.com/2019/04/28/industry-expert-on-teslas-motors-theyve-got-magic/ |archivedate=2019-09-21 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[cooling system]]<!--good wikilink not found--> is integrated to reduce size and cost.<ref name=jalop2018-12-12>{{cite web |title=The Tesla Model 3 'Superbottle' Easter Egg Is a Fascinating Packaging Solution |url=https://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-3s-superbottle-easter-egg-is-a-fascin-1830992728 |website=Jalopnik |date= December 12, 2018|language=en-us |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191219054117/https://jalopnik.com/the-tesla-model-3s-superbottle-easter-egg-is-a-fascin-1830992728 |archivedate=2019-12-19 |url-status=live}}</ref>
