The '''Tesla Cybertruck''' is an [[Electric car|all-electric]], [[battery electric vehicle|battery-powered]], [[light commercial vehicle]] in development by [[Tesla, Inc.]] Three models have been announced, with range estimates of {{convert|250–500|miles|km|round=10|abbr=out}} and an estimated [[0 to 60 mph|0–60 mph time]] of 2.9–6.5 seconds, depending on the model.<ref name=tesla20191122 />

The stated goal of Tesla in developing the Cybertruck is to provide a sustainable-energy substitute for the roughly 6,500 fossil-fuel-powered trucks sold per day in the United States.<ref name=tesla20191122 /><ref name="musk-20130507">{{cite tweet|number=331796308631367681|date=2013-05-07|access-date=2019-11-20|first=Elon|last=Musk|user=elonmusk|authorlink=Elon Musk|title=Tesla priority is electrification of cars, so priority is Model S, Model X, then mass market third gen vehicle & truck}}</ref><ref name="swisher-20181105">{{cite interview|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/2/18053424/elon-musk-tesla-spacex-boring-company-self-driving-cars-saudi-twitter-kara-swisher-decode-podcast|first=Elon|last=Musk|subject-link=Elon Musk|title=Elon Musk: The Recode interview|interviewer=[[Kara Swisher]]|date=2018-11-05|work=[[Recode]]|via=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|quote=personally most excited about the pickup truck. … futuristic-like cyberpunk, "[[Blade Runner (franchise)|Blade Runner]]" pickup truck. … don't know if a lot of people will buy this pickup truck or not, but I don’t care. … We wanna get gasoline, diesel pickup trucks off the road. … it's the thing that I am personally most fired up about|access-date=16 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912031821/https://www.vox.com/2018/11/2/18053424/elon-musk-tesla-spacex-boring-company-self-driving-cars-saudi-twitter-kara-swisher-decode-podcast|archive-date=12 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

The base price of the [[rear-wheel drive]] model of the vehicle will be [[United States dollar|US$]]39,900, with [[all-wheel drive]] models starting at $49,900.<ref name=mccPodcast20190529>{{cite interview|first=Elon|last=Musk|subject-link=Elon Musk|interviewer=Ryan McCaffrey|date=2019-05-29<!-- date of interview at Tesla HQ -->|location=Tesla Headquarters, [[Palo Alto, California]]|title=Episode 200: My Elon Musk Interview|series=Ride the Lightning|url=https://teslapodcast.libsyn.com/episode-200-my-elon-musk-interview|format=offset 51:02|quote=we don't want it to be really expensive, … it's got to start at less than $50,000 dollars, it's got to be like $49,000 dollars starting price, {{abbr|max|maximum}} … ideally less … it has got to be something that is affordable … you've got to be able to get a really great truck for $49,000, or less, … it's going to have incredible functionality, from a load-carrying standpoint, look amazing, … but it won't look like a normal truck … it's going to look pretty [[science fiction|sci-fi]], … not going to be for everyone, if somebody just wants to have a truck that looks like trucks have looked for the last twenty years, thirty or forty years, then this truck probably isn't for them, going to be a truck that is more capable than other trucks … it'll be a better truck than an equivalent … better truck than an [[Ford F-150|F-150]] in terms of truck-like functionality, be better sports car than a standard [[Porsche 911|911]] … [the teaser image] is the front … like a Bladerunner truck|access-date=14 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191013150842/https://teslapodcast.libsyn.com/episode-200-my-elon-musk-interview|archive-date=13 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/21/tesla-cybertruck-unveiled.html|title=Tesla unveils its first electric pickup, the Cybertruck, starting at $39,900|work=CNBC|date=2019-11-21|access-date=2019-11-22|first=Lora|last=Kolodny|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122043542/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/21/tesla-cybertruck-unveiled.html|archive-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>
Cybertruck production is slated to begin in 2021, with more models being offered by 2022.<!-- this is sourced in the article body, and does not really _need_ a repeat of the source here, per WP:MOS:LEADCITE-->

== History ==
In 2012<ref name="musk-201208">{{cite tweet|number=230487450882019328 |first=Elon|last=Musk |user=elonmusk|authorlink=Elon Musk|date=2012-08-01|access-date=2019-11-21|title=Would love to make a Tesla supertruck with crazy torque, dynamic air suspension and corners like its on rails.}}</ref> and 2013 Elon Musk discussed the desire to build a truck with load-compensating suspension, making comparisons with a [[Ford F-250]].<ref name="musk-2013-teslive">{{cite AV media|title=2013 Teslive Event|first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8n-xsEjq7pk&t=32m |date=2013-07-13|publisher=Tesla|location=[[San Jose, California]]|conference=Teslive 2013|quote=I am quite keen on building a truck … [[air suspension]] that dynamically adjusts the load and keeps the angle of the truck correct … was driving an [[Ford F-250|F-250]] down [[Interstate 405 (California)|the 405]] … it was resonating}}</ref><ref name="musk-20130525">{{cite tweet|number=338117807910813696 |first=Elon|last=Musk|authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|date=2013-05-25|title=Would love to do a pickup truck. Something {{abbr|w|with}} ultra low {{abbr|cg|centre of gravity}} for sports car handling, dynamic air suspension &amp; mega torque.}}</ref> In early-2014 Musk predicted 4–5 years before work could start on the product.<ref>{{cite interview|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvH825IWPM0&t=2m8s |first=Elon|last=Musk |subject-link=Elon Musk|interviewer=[[Poppy Harlow]]|department=CNN Money|work=CNN|date=2014-01-16 |title=When will you be able to afford a Tesla?|via=Youtube|type=video offset: 2:08|quote=Yeah, we'd like to produce an electric pickup truck; we're not really thinking much about that, but that is part of our long-term plans.  Would imagine that is probably something like 4‒5 years.}}</ref>

In mid-2016, Musk outlined the intent for a new kind of consumer pickup truck,<ref name="part-deux-20160720">{{cite web|publisher=Tesla, Inc.|url=https://www.tesla.com/blog/master-plan-part-deux?redirect=no|title=Master Plan, Part Deux|first=Elon|last=Musk|date=2016-07-20|access-date=2019-11-16|quote=With the [[Tesla Model 3|Model 3]], a [[Tesla Model Y|future compact SUV]] and a new kind of pickup truck, we plan to address most of the consumer market.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116060648/https://www.tesla.com/blog/master-plan-part-deux%3Fredirect%3Dno|archive-date=16 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and suggested using the same [[chassis]] for a van and a pickup truck.<ref name="musk-2016">{{cite tweet|number=759798110470205440 |first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|date=2016-07-31 |title=probably makes sense to build off the pickup truck chassis}}</ref> In late-2017, the size was estimated to be at least that of a [[Ford F-150]], in order to be large enough to enable a "[[wikt:game-changing|game-changing]]" feature.<ref name="musk-2017-12-26">{{cite tweet|first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|date=2017-12-26 |number=945729229001334784 |title=Similar total size. Maybe slightly bigger to account for a really gamechanging (I think) feature I'd like to add.}}</ref> During the [[Tesla Semi]] and [[Tesla Roadster (2020)|Tesla Roadster]] unveiling in November 2017, a picture of a "pickup truck that can carry a pickup truck" was displayed.<ref name="musk-20171214">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RRmepp7i5g&t=9m30s |title=Tesla Semi & Roadster Unveil|via=Youtube|first=Elon|last=Musk |publisher=[[Tesla, Inc.]]|quote=For interests sake we created a pickup truck version of the [[Tesla Semi]].  It's a pickup truck that can carry a pickup truck.  By the way, you can legally drive that—it shouldn't be legal, but…—you'll be able to legally drive that with a normal driver's license.  It's kind of wrong, but I like it.}}</ref> Background ideas had been in preparation for nearly five years.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=945713737729634304 |user=elonmusk|first=Elon|last=Musk |author-link=Elon Musk|date=2017-12-26|access-date=2019-11-20 |title=I promise that we will make a pickup truck right after Model Y. Have had the core design/engineering elements in my mind for almost 5 years. Am dying to build it.}}</ref>

In late 2018, Musk anticipated a prototype to be ready to show in 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1072488765753618437 |user=elonmusk|first=Elon|last=Musk |author-link=Elon Musk|date=2018-12-11|access-date=2019-11-20 |title=I'm dying to make a pickup truck so bad … we might have a prototype to unveil next year}}</ref>

In March 2019, following the [[Tesla Model Y]] launch, [[Elon Musk]] distributed a [[teaser campaign|teaser image]] of a vehicle described as having a [[cyberpunk]] or ''[[Blade Runner (franchise)|Blade Runner]]'' style,<ref name="ibt-20190319">{{cite news|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/tesla-blade-runner-everything-we-know-about-elon-musks-6-seater-pickup-truck-2771401|title=Tesla Blade Runner: Everything We Know About Elon Musk's 6-Seater Pickup Truck|first=Jerome|last=Santos|date=4 March 2019|access-date=19 March 2019|work=[[International Business Times]]|quote=pickup truck …  dual motor all-wheel drive, … outlet for up to 240-volts normally used for heavy-duty tools and can tow up to 300,000 pounds. … Tesla pickup truck will look like a proper truck, a design barely seen in electric vehicles so far. … will have a "cyberpunk, [[Blade Runner (franchise)|Blade Runner]]-like" look, … a futuristic design.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306160850/https://www.ibtimes.com/tesla-blade-runner-everything-we-know-about-elon-musks-6-seater-pickup-truck-2771401|archive-date=6 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> with the form resembling a futuristic [[armoured personnel carrier]].<ref name="musk-20191014">{{cite tweet|number=1183583315263131648 |user=elonmusk|first=Elon|last=Musk |author-link=Elon Musk|date=2019-10-14|title=Cybertruck doesn't look like anything I've seen bouncing around the Internet. It's closer to an armored personnel carrier from the future.}}</ref><ref name="musk-20191105-space-pitch-day">{{cite interview|first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|access-date=2019-11-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lS3nIyetS4I&t=10m47s |interviewer=John F. Thompson|date=2019-11-05|location=San Francisco|work=Space Pitch Day|title=Elon Musk's Complete interview at Air Force Space Pitch Day|quote=We're going to come out with the Tesla pickup truck which we call the Cybertruck.  I mean, it looks like an [[Armoured Personnel Carrier]] from the future. Yeah, it won't look like a normal truck and people might not like it.  I like it!  It's going to look like it came from a movie set when it goes down the road; …what is that thing?  It's literally [[bullet proof]]. … If I can elaborate on that: a lot of times people try to make products that they think others would love, but they don't love them, themselves; if you don't love the product, you should not expect that others will. … Know your own heart, and if it's compelling to you, it will be compelling to others.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=1102345986117033984 |first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|date=2019-03-04|access-date=2019-11-20 |title=Yes. Personally, I’m most excited by the Tesla Truck. Maybe it will be too futuristic for most people, but I love it.}}</ref> It was rumored to be named the ''Model B''.<ref name="InsideEVs-20190806">{{cite web |url= https://insideevs.com/news/363685/tesla-pickup-truck-model-b/ |title= Tesla Electric Pickup Truck To Be Called Model B? |author= Eric Loveday |date= 6 August 2019 |publisher= Inside EVs |access-date= 1 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191130030729/https://insideevs.com/news/363685/tesla-pickup-truck-model-b/ |archive-date= 30 November 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name="IBT-20190829">{{cite news |url= http://ibtimes.com/tesla-model-b-release-it-elon-musks-pickup-2819920 |title= Tesla Model B Release: Is It Elon Musk's Pickup? |date= 29 August 2019 |author= Lorraine Lorenz |newspaper= International Business Times |access-date= 1 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191206222112/https://www.ibtimes.com/tesla-model-b-release-it-elon-musks-pickup-2819920 |archive-date= 6 December 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name="PopMech-20191121">{{cite magazine |url= https://www.popularmechanics.com/cars/hybrid-electric/a29787807/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-truck-what-we-know/ |title= Everything We Know About Tesla's Mysterious New Pickup Truck |author= Eric Adams |date= 21 November 2019 |magazine= Popular Mechanics |access-date= 1 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191126025544/https://www.popularmechanics.com/cars/hybrid-electric/a29787807/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-truck-what-we-know/ |archive-date= 26 November 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref> Tesla filed for a trademark on "Cybrtrk", which was granted under [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] 88682748.<ref name=Trademarkia-88682748-20191106>{{cite web |url= https://trademark.trademarkia.com/cybrtrk-88682748.html |title= Cybrtrk Trademark Information |id= USPTO 88682748 |date= 6 November 2019 |publisher= Trademarkia |access-date= 6 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191206132926/https://trademark.trademarkia.com/cybrtrk-88682748.html |archive-date= 6 December 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>

In mid-2019, the [[towing capacity]] of the vehicle was stated to meet or exceed that of a [[Ford F-150]].<ref name="lawler-20191106">{{cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2019/06/11/tesla-annual-shareholders-meeting-2019/|title=Elon Musk talks up Tesla's 'Cyberpunk truck,' and 400-mile range EVs|first=Richard|last=Lawler|date=2019-11-06|access-date=2019-07-28|work=[[Engadget]]|quote=The "Cyberpunk truck" … being designed to "meet or exceed an [[Ford F-150|F-150]] ‒ if the F-150 can do it then a Tesla Truck should be able to do it." … that if "you're driving it down the road, it will look like it came out of a sci-fi movie" and called it "the coolest car I've ever seen."|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711174744/https://www.engadget.com/2019/06/11/tesla-annual-shareholders-meeting-2019/|archive-date=11 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  In June 2019, Musk noted that an [[amphibious vehicle]] design concept—based partly on [[Wet Nellie]], the submarine car from the film ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]''—was possible.<ref name="musk-20190611-shareholders-water">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Va5i42D13cI&t=52m26s|title=Tesla Annual Shareholders Meeting|date=2019-06-11|first=Elon|last=Musk|quote=[Musk] a car that can go in the water basically?  [Questioner] On, or under, or both, the water?  [Musk] It's funny you should mention that … if you make it a big bigger then you can actually have a [[submarine]] car.  It's like technically possible.  I think the market for this will be small; small but enthusiastic.  So… we do actually have a design for a submarine car.}}</ref><ref name="musk-20191121-2312-water">{{cite tweet|number=1197638937109336066|user=elonmusk|first=Elon|last=Musk|authorlink=Elon Musk|date=2019-11-21 <!-- 23:12 -->|title=Cybertruck design influenced partly by The Spy Who Loved Me|link=no}}</ref> Musk had bought a Wet Nellie used in the filming at a 2013 [[Sotheby's]] auction.<ref name=cnbc20191122>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/22/james-bond-lotus-sports-car-elon-musk-bought-inspired-tesla-cybertruck.html|title=This is the James Bond sports car Elon Musk bought for nearly $1 million that inspired Tesla Cybertruck|last=Huddleston|first=Tom|date=2019-11-22|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191127225950/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/22/james-bond-lotus-sports-car-elon-musk-bought-inspired-tesla-cybertruck.html|archive-date=27 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In response to queries for an unveiling date,<ref name="musk-20190304">{{cite tweet|user=elonmusk|number=1102343438668713986 |date=2019-03-04|first=Elon|last=Musk |author-link=Elon Musk|access-date=2019-10-15|title=No, that [Tesla Truck] unveil is later this year [2019]}}</ref> Musk stated in late July "We're close, but the magic is in the final details. Maybe 2 to 3 months", indicating late-2019.<ref name="musk-20190727">{{cite tweet|date=2019-07-27|first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|number=1155184195586519040 |title=We're close, but the magic is in the final details. Maybe 2 to 3 months.}}</ref>  The unveiling was later scheduled for 21 November 2019 at the Tesla Design Studio, next to [[SpaceX]] headquarters in Los Angeles—the same month, year and location that the movie ''[[Blade Runner]]'' was set in.<ref name="musk-20191009">{{cite tweet|number=1181990398379483137 |first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|title=No change|date=2019-09-07}}</ref><ref name="20191106-musk-blade-runner">{{cite tweet|number=1192117194756243457 |first=Elon|last=Musk |user=elonmusk|authorlink=Elon Musk|date=2019-11-06|access-date=2019-11-06 |title=The date is strangely familiar …|link=no|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fu7jN2_2pE |title=Blade Runner – Opening Titles |via=YouTube |access-date=6 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106171138/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fu7jN2_2pE |archive-date=6 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="20191106-musk-date">{{cite tweet|number=1192113294036754432 |first=Elon|last=Musk |user=elonmusk|authorlink=Elon Musk|date=2019-11-06|access-date=2019-11-06 |title=Cybertruck unveil on <time datetime="2019-11-21" title="21 November 2019">Nov 21</time> in {{abbr|LA|Los Angeles}} near SpaceX rocket factory}}</ref><ref name="musk-20190907">{{cite tweet|number=1170401244310949888 |first=Elon|last=Musk |authorlink=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|title=[We're almost there] … November [2019] most likely|date=2019-09-07}}</ref> The truck was launched under a graffiti-themed logo of "Cybertruck", and a new trademark request was filed with the graffiti logo at the same time.<ref name=Wired-20191126>{{cite magazine |url= https://www.wired.com/story/cybertruck-swag-floods-amazon-etsy/ |title= Cybertruck Swag Has Flooded Amazon and Etsy |author= Louise Matsakis |date= 26 November 2019 |magazine= Wired |access-date= 6 December 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191130081124/https://www.wired.com/story/cybertruck-swag-floods-amazon-etsy/ |archive-date= 30 November 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>

== Features ==
The truck will use [[self-leveling suspension]] which compensates for variable load and some models will have [[all-wheel drive]].<ref name=MTspec20191122/> Other standard features include on-board [[power inverter]]s for supplying both 120 and 240-volt electricity, allowing use of [[power tools]] without a [[portable generator]].<ref name=MTspec20191122/> An [[air compressor]] for powering [[pneumatic tool]]s is included.<ref name=MTspec20191122/> The exterior stainless steel sheet-metal is [[Bulletproofing|bullet-resistant]] against [[9 mm caliber]] bullets.<ref name="MTbullet">{{cite magazine |last=Ireson |first=Nelson |title=Is the Tesla Cybertruck *Really* Bulletproof? |url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-bulletproof-stainless-steel-body/ |magazine=[[Motor Trend]] |quote='If fully hardened, 3mm of 301 stainless is more than adequate to stop any 9mm Luger round I can think of...' said Iain Harrison, editor-in-chief of Recoil as well as a competitive shooter and former British Army captain. ... Elon Musk says the laminated windshield, which appears to be completely flat, will stop a 9mm round, as well. We tested its strength by dropping weighed metal spheres from various heights. It didn't break. |date=2019-11-22 |access-date=2019-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122155828/https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-bulletproof-stainless-steel-body/ |archive-date=22 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> All vehicles will also come with [[Tesla Autopilot]], and will have the hardware capabilities for fully autonomous operation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/auto/tesla-cybertruck-pickup-revealed |title=Tesla Cybertruck pickup revealed with bulletproof body and $39,900 starting price |first=Gary |last=Gastelu |work=Fox News |location=US |date=2019-11-22 |access-date=2019-11-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125173343/https://www.foxnews.com/auto/tesla-cybertruck-pickup-revealed |archive-date=25 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of November 2019, Tesla was accepting pre-orders for $100, with a $7,000 'full self-driving' option.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tesla.com/cybertruck/design|title=Design Your Cybertruck|last=|first=|date=|website=www.tesla.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122061840/https://www.tesla.com/cybertruck/design|archive-date=22 November 2019|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>

The range of the Cybertruck varies from {{convert|250-500|miles|km|round=50|abbr=out}}, depending on configuration selections.

=== Interior ===
The interior of the prototype unveiled on 21 November 2019 includes a 17-inch center display, seating for 6 using two bench seats with the front middle seat being a fold-down center arm rest, a digital rear-view camera based mirror, a race car style steering yoke, and a dashboard with a surface resembling marble.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yTw1eOpjHi4 |title=Riding in a Tesla Cybertruck is Unlike Any Other Tesla |first=Ben |last=Sullins |access-date=2019-11-26 |via=YouTube |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128024045/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yTw1eOpjHi4 |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The rear middle seat  folds down to allow loading long cargo extending into the cab from the vault (enclosed lockable bed).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/top-10-tesla-cybertruck-hidden-features-you-may-have-missed/|title=Top 10 Tesla Cybertruck hidden features you may have missed|last=Alvarez|first=Simon|date=2019-11-26|website=TESLARATI|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129150850/https://www.teslarati.com/top-10-tesla-cybertruck-hidden-features-you-may-have-missed/|archive-date=29 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The "marble look" dashboard of the unveil prototype vehicle was a [[Paper composite panels|paper composite]] material made from "paper, wood-based fibers, natural wood pigments and non-petroleum based resins."<ref name=trati20191125>{{cite news |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-marble-dashboard-paper-material/ |title=Tesla Cybertruck's 'marble' dashboard is actually made from paper and it's genius |work=Teslarati |date=25 November 2019 |access-date=26 November 2019 |first=Joey |last=Klender |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191224051245/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-marble-dashboard-paper-material/ |archive-date=24 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Tesla Cybertruck unveiling.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Rear view]]
=== Vault (bed) ===
The bed of the truck is {{convert|6.5|ft}} long and similar to a conventional pickup truck bed with tailgate. It has sloped side walls and an integral motorized [[roller shutter]] style [[tonneau]] cover to improve the aerodynamics of the vehicle. Because of the additional security this provides, Tesla terms this {{convert|100|ft3|adj=on}} enclosed space "the vault". It includes [[Solid-state lighting|LED light strips]] along each side, an additional under-floor storage space behind the rear wheels, 110 and 220&nbsp;[[Volt|V]] [[Alternating current|AC]] outlets, and a [[compressed air]] outlet for [[pneumatic tools]].<ref name=Alvarez>{{cite web |url=https://www.teslarati.com/top-10-tesla-cybertruck-hidden-features-you-may-have-missed/ |title=Top 10 Tesla Cybertruck hidden features you may have missed |last=Alvarez |first=Simon |date=26 November 2019 |website=Teslarati |language=en-US |access-date=2019-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129150850/https://www.teslarati.com/top-10-tesla-cybertruck-hidden-features-you-may-have-missed/ |archive-date=29 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> One article claims that there is a pass-through to the cabin for long cargo,{{r|Alvarez}} the displayed prototype lacks any corresponding opening in the front of the bed.<ref>{{cite web |title=ALL CyberTruck discussion |author=Mongo |date=26 November 2019 |website=Tesla Motors Club |type=forum posting |access-date=2019-11-27 |url=https://teslamotorsclub.com/tmc/posts/4241098/ |quote=the bed has no pass through that I see}}</ref> Elon Musk indicated in a tweet that the cabin's climate control will also be available in the vault for uses such as camping.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-camping-mode-hvac-truck-bed/|title=Tesla Cybertruck owners will be able to “camp” in the truck bed, says Elon Musk|last=Randell Suba|date=2019-12-18|website=TESLARATI|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218152125/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-camping-mode-hvac-truck-bed/|archive-date=18 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2019/12/18/tesla-cybertruck-bed-access-2nd-row-great-camping-machine/|title=Tesla Cybertruck's bed accessible from 2nd row, making a great camping machine|last=Dow|first=Jameson|date=2019-12-18|website=Electrek|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218152126/https://electrek.co/2019/12/18/tesla-cybertruck-bed-access-2nd-row-great-camping-machine/|archive-date=18 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> One feature demonstrated on the prototype, but not explicitly advertised, is a ramp that extends from the tail gate to the ground for loading cargo.{{cn|date=December 2019}}<!-- it is unclear that this is actually any sort of an intended feature for the production truck; if not, it probably should not be in this section on Features -->

== Design ==
The Cybertruck uses [[unibody]] construction (termed an "[[exoskeleton]]" by Tesla)<ref>{{cite news |title=Musk says it's really tough, not fake tough |first=Ciprian |last=Florea |date=23 November 2019 |journal=TopSpeed |url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/car-news/tesla-cybertruck-exoskeleton-and-design-explained-ar187129.html |quote=Tesla designed an exoskeleton, a fancier word for unibody layout}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What is Cybertruck Exoskeleton? |author=Ollie |website=Teslas Motors Club |type=forum post |date=24 November 2019 |url=https://teslamotorsclub.com/tmc/threads/what-is-cybertruck-exoskeleton.174936/ |quote=All modern cars except most pickup trucks have a frameless exoskeleton, AKA monocoque or unibody.}}</ref>  like most passenger cars, rather than the [[body-on-frame]] construction which is typical of trucks,<ref>{{cite news |title=Tesla: Cybertruck uses stainless-steel 'exoskeleton' rather than traditional body-on-frame |first=John |last=Huetter |date=22 November 2019 |journal=Repairer Driven News |url=https://www.repairerdrivennews.com/2019/11/22/tesla-cybertruck-uses-stainless-steel-exoskeleton-rather-than-traditional-body-on-frame/}}</ref> as a standard [[vehicle frame]] would conflict with the under-floor battery pack.<ref name=tc20191122>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Burns |title=Here's why the Tesla Cybertruck has its crazy look |quote=Saved-You-A-Click: Because it's a unibody truck |date=22 November 2019 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/11/22/heres-why-the-tesla-cybertruck-has-its-crazy-look/ |work=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=25 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126015127/https://techcrunch.com/2019/11/22/heres-why-the-tesla-cybertruck-has-its-crazy-look/ |archive-date=26 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  It uses unusually thick {{cvt|3|mm|in|frac=8}} [[SAE steel grades#300 Series—austenitic chromium-nickel alloys|30x-series]]{{efn|Numerous media sources are misreading "30x", an industry standard three-digit alloy identifier for [[austenitic stainless steel]] with the last digit unspecified, as a multiplication sign ("30&times;") and erroneously reporting that the truck will use steel has been cold-rolled 30 times.}} [[Cold-formed steel|cold-rolled]] [[stainless steel]] body panels, which cannot be [[Stamping (metalworking)|stamped]] like conventional automobile parts.<ref name=MTreynolds20191122 />  The panels can only be bent along straight lines,<ref name=MTreynolds20191122 /> resulting in a very distinctive [[facet]]ed design which has been called "[[low-poly]]" or likened to [[origami]].<ref name="MTbullet" />  This material is the same material [[SpaceX]] uses on their [[SpaceX Starship|Starship]], because it distributes stress more evenly and allows for more interior volume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.automoblog.net/2019/11/22/tesla-cybertruck-overview/|title=Tesla Cybertruck: The Future of Trucks? We're Not Sure But We Like It|last=Reyes|first=Alvin|date=2019-11-22|website=Automoblog|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222021127/https://www.automoblog.net/2019/11/22/tesla-cybertruck-overview/|archive-date=22 December 2019|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref> Earlier design concepts for Cybertruck had included using [[titanium]] for the outer panels, but this was later switched to stainless steel for additional strength.<ref name="musk-20191124-titanium">{{cite tweet|first=Elon|last=Musk|author-link=Elon Musk|user=elonmusk|number=1198702136231526401|date=2019-11-24|access-date=2019-11-30|title=Starship steel decision came first. We were going to use titanium skins for Cybertruck, but cold-rolled 30X stainless is much stronger.}}</ref>

=== Specifications ===
The [[powertrain]] is similar to the Model S/X,{{clarify|which version of motor? the original Model S/X motor, or has there been some later upgrade to the motor design|date=November 2019}} with an inductive rear motor and the Model 3's permanent-magnet in front for the medium model.<ref name=MTreynolds20191122>{{cite magazine |last1=Reynolds |first1=Kim |title=How Tesla's Cybertruck Turns Auto Manufacturing and Engineering Upside-Down |url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-engineering-manufacturing |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191122170053/https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-engineering-manufacturing |archive-date=2019-11-22 |url-status=live|magazine=[[Motor Trend]] |date=2019-11-22 |quote=The plusses for a folded stainless steel, origami truck are compelling: no paint shop and no expensive tooling. No Godzilla-scale stamping machines stomping it with multiple strikes. groove the steel where it's supposed to fold (avoiding cracks) and bend it on simple, cheap machines}}</ref> Other versions are single-motor rear wheel drive, or tri-motor with one front and two rear motors.<ref name=MTspec20191122/>

Similar to other Tesla models, the cybertruck can be pre-ordered with Full Self Driving software upgrade, adding an additional $7,000 to the price of the configuration.<ref name="tesla20191122">{{cite web |url=https://www.tesla.com/cybertruck/design |title=Design Your Cybertruck |date=2019-11-22 |website=Tesla website |access-date=2019-11-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122061840/https://www.tesla.com/cybertruck/design |archive-date=22 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=MTspec20191122>{{cite magazine |last1=Seabaugh |first1=Christian |title=How Fast is the Tesla Cybertruck? And How Much Can It Tow? |url=https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-fast-0-60-range-payload-towing |magazine=[[Motor Trend]] |date=2019-11-22 |access-date=22 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122154329/https://www.motortrend.com/news/tesla-cybertruck-electric-pickup-fast-0-60-range-payload-towing |archive-date=22 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

