== Unveiling ==
{{multiple image|perrow = 1|total_width=240
| image1 = 20191121-tesla-cybertruck-window-steel-ball-before.jpg
| image2 = Tesla Cybertruck damaged window.jpg
| image3 = 20191121-tesla-cybertruck-shattered-windows-url.jpg
| footer = Window damage caused by [[Franz von Holzhausen]] during unveiling event
}}

The Cybertruck was unveiled at the Tesla Design Studio in Los Angeles on 21 November 2019.  During the presentation, Musk demonstrated the durability of the vehicle and its materials. Despite successful drop tests conducted on a pane of the specialized 'Tesla armor glass' and a successful pre-show test where a steel ball was thrown at the windows of the truck itself by chief of design [[Franz von Holzhausen]] with apparently no damage,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Musk |first1=Elon |title=Franz throws steel ball at Cybertruck window right before launch. Guess we have some improvements to make before production haha.pic.twitter.com/eB0o4tlPoz |url=https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1198090787520598016 |website=@elonmusk |language=en |date=22 November 2019 |access-date=23 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123223939/https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1198090787520598016 |archive-date=23 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> the windows were damaged when Holzhausen repeated the test during the show. Musk jokingly exclaimed that "the ball didn't make it through" and "we'll fix it in post" after the unexpected outcomes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/21/20975475/tesla-cybertruck-announcement-musk-electric-truck-pickup-features-range-price-release-date|title=Elon Musk just announced the new Tesla Cybertruck|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=2019-11-21|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126153855/https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/21/20975475/tesla-cybertruck-announcement-musk-electric-truck-pickup-features-range-price-release-date|archive-date=26 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He later explained that the windows were damaged because in an earlier demonstration, the door was hit by a sledgehammer and that cracked the base of the glass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/25/20981489/tesla-cybertruck-glass-window-fail-elon-musk-explanation|title=Elon Musk explains why Tesla's Cybertruck windows smashed during presentation|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Vincent|first=James|date=25 November 2019|access-date=25 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125123816/https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/25/20981489/tesla-cybertruck-glass-window-fail-elon-musk-explanation|archive-date=25 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

At the end of the presentation, the [[Tesla Cyberquad]], an [[all-terrain vehicle]] (ATV), was driven onto the bed of the Cybertruck using built-in ramps in the [[Trunk (car)#Tailgate|tailgate]]. The Cyberquad was plugged into the Cybertruck's onboard power outlet to charge the Cyberquad batteries. The ATV will be available for sale as an optional package with the Cybertruck.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/21/20977300/tesla-atv-electric-features-range-price-release-date-announcement-elon-musk-all-terrain|title=Tesla made an ATV to complement its futuristic Cybertruck|date=21 November 2019|access-date=5 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191125075008/https://www.theverge.com/2019/11/21/20977300/tesla-atv-electric-features-range-price-release-date-announcement-elon-musk-all-terrain|archive-date=25 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Reactions ==
The Cybertruck unveiling event was covered heavily by traditional media and online blogs/social media. In social media, many commentators expressed dislike of the sharp contours and unusual exterior of the Cybertruck.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/22/tech/cybertruck-tesla-pickup-truck-jokes/index.html |title=Tesla's Cybertruck has become the butt of every internet joke |first=Matt |last=McFarland |work=CNN |location=US |date=22 November 2019 |access-date=27 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122235642/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/11/22/tech/cybertruck-tesla-pickup-truck-jokes/index.html |archive-date=22 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Tesla, Inc. stock was down 6% following the Cybertruck announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2019/11/22/tesla-tsla-stock-down-electric-pickup-unveiling-market-missing-point/|title=Tesla (TSLA) stock down after electric pickup unveiling — market is missing the point|last=Lambert|first=Fred|date=2019-11-22|website=Electrek|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191122170238/https://electrek.co/2019/11/22/tesla-tsla-stock-down-electric-pickup-unveiling-market-missing-point/|archive-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Relevance inline|connection of this to the Cybertruck is not established. Stocks go up/down on any given day for many reasons in the minds of the myriad buyers/sellers that exchanged cash for equity.|date=December 2019}}

On 23 November 2019, Elon Musk tweeted that Tesla had received 146,000 pre-orders in the first 1.5 days after the unveiling—each requiring a {{USD|100}} refundable deposit—with 42% choosing the dual-motor configuration, 41% choosing the tri-motor configuration, and 17% choosing the single-motor configuration.<ref name=trati20191124alvarez>{{cite web |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-vault-bed-cover-in-action-video/ |title=Watching Tesla Cybertruck's 'vault' bed cover in action is hypnotizing |first=Simon |last=Alvarez |work=Teslarati |location=US |date=24 November 2019 |access-date=27 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124220133/https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-vault-bed-cover-in-action-video/ |archive-date=24 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|author-link=Elon Musk|number=1198344195317985280|title=146k Cybertruck orders so far, with 42% choosing dual, 41% tri & 17% single motor|last=Musk|first=Elon|date=2019-11-23|user=elonmusk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> The number reached 250,000 on 26 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1199526897887195136?s=20|title=250k|last=Musk|first=Elon|date=2019-11-26|website=@elonmusk|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>

Additionally, a video of the Cybertruck pulling a rear-wheel-drive Ford F-150 uphill in a [[tug of war]] resulted in 14,000 comments and 619,000 likes on Twitter.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1198751258384818176|title=Cybertruck pulls F-150 uphill|last=Musk|first=Elon|date=2019-11-24|user=elonmusk|author-link=Elon Musk|link=no|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref> A Ford vice president tweeted that he wanted to arrange a rematch,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/302718-ford-wants-rematch-in-tesla-cybertruck-vs-f-150-tug-of-war |title=Ford Wants Rematch in Tesla Cybertruck vs. F-150 Tug of War |work=ExtremeTech |access-date=28 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128135932/https://www.extremetech.com/extreme/302718-ford-wants-rematch-in-tesla-cybertruck-vs-f-150-tug-of-war |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and while Musk agreed in principle,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/26/tesla-ford-challenged-elon-musk-to-a-tug-of-war-between-pickup-trucks.html |title=Ford challenged Tesla to an 'apples to apples' tug-of-war between pickup trucks — Musk says 'bring it on' |work=CNBC |access-date=28 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128033323/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/26/tesla-ford-challenged-elon-musk-to-a-tug-of-war-between-pickup-trucks.html |archive-date=28 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> a Ford spokesperson later clarified that the tweet had been 'tongue in cheek'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/26/ford-vs-tesla-elon-musk-game-for-a-cybertruck-rematch-against-f-150|title=Ford vs. Tesla: Elon Musk game for a Cybertruck rematch against F-150|work=NYPost|first=Noah|last=Manskar|date=2019-11-26|access-date=2019-12-19|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219205025/https://nypost.com/2019/11/26/ford-vs-tesla-elon-musk-game-for-a-cybertruck-rematch-against-f-150/|archive-date=19 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>

In January 2020, [[Automobile Magazine]] named Cybertruck the "Concept Car of the Year" for 2019.<ref name=trati20200106>{{cite news |url=https://www.teslarati.com/tesla-cybertruck-concept-car-of-the-year-award |author=Joey Klender |title=Tesla Cybertruck wins Concept Car of the Year award for its insanely unique design |work=Teslarati |date=6 January 2020 |access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref>

== Production ==
<!-- Placeholder for Cybertruck Gigafactory . Nashville is not confirmed as bid https://electrek.co/2020/03/11/tesla-cybertruck-gigafactory-nashville-elon-musk-incentives-workforce/ -->
{{As of|November 2019}}, Tesla Cybertruck production was scheduled to start in late 2021 and expand to offer more configurations in 2022.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/electric-tesla-pickup-truck-announcement-specs-cost-photos/ |title=Tesla Cybertruck: Elon Musk's Pickup Truck Has Arrived|work=Wired|access-date=2019-11-23|language=en|issn=1059-1028|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191123014603/https://www.wired.com/story/electric-tesla-pickup-truck-announcement-specs-cost-photos/ |archive-date=23 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Joplin, Missouri|city of Joplin, Missouri]] offered land and incentives to attract production of the vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lambert |first1=Fred |title=Tesla Cybertruck Gigafactory: Missouri offers land and incentive package in race for factory |url=https://electrek.co/2020/03/17/tesla-cybertruck-gigafactory-missouri-land-incentive/ |website=Electrek |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>

=== Market potential ===
In the United States, the [[total addressable market]] for full-sized pickup trucks is over two million vehicles per year.<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2019/11/20/elon-musk-cybertruck-will-thrill--tesla-fans-but-its-pickup-market-potential-is-a-puzzler/ |first=Alan|last=Ohnsman|date=2019-11-20|access-date=2019-11-22|magazine=[[Forbes]]|title=Elon Musk's 'Cybertruck' Will Thrill Tesla Fans, But Its Pickup Market Potential Is A Puzzler|quote=U.S. sales of full-size pickups, the world’s primary market for such vehicles, surpasses 2 million units annually, and volume leaders Ford, GM and FiatChrysler's Ram battle to retain buyer loyalty and bragging rights in a space where median prices approach $50,000.|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191122113857/https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2019/11/20/elon-musk-cybertruck-will-thrill--tesla-fans-but-its-pickup-market-potential-is-a-puzzler/ |archive-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It has been argued that the Cybertruck will be able to take advantage of the Tesla Network of shared vehicles<ref name="part-deux-20160720" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://electrek.co/2019/04/05/tesla-network-details-april-22/ |title=More details on "Tesla Network" autonomous rideshare service coming in April 22 webcast|first=Jameson|last=Dow |date=2019-05-05|work=Electrek |access-date=2019-11-25|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190529030124/https://electrek.co/2019/04/05/tesla-network-details-april-22/ |archive-date=29 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> to generate an income stream,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicswebinstitute.org/essays/tesla-pickup.htm |title=Tesla Cybertruck: your next income stream?|first=Valentino|last=Piana |access-date=2019-11-25|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191207172551/http://www.economicswebinstitute.org/essays/tesla-pickup.htm |archive-date=7 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> if the latter were to become available in United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/04/22/tesla-plans-to-launch-a-robotaxi-network-in-2020/ |title=Tesla plans to launch a robotaxi network in 2020|date=2019-04-22|work=Techcrunch |first=Kirsten|last=Korosec |access-date=2019-11-25|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191106072639/https://techcrunch.com/2019/04/22/tesla-plans-to-launch-a-robotaxi-network-in-2020/ |archive-date=6 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and worldwide.<ref name="part-deux-20160720" />

